Author::::derekcolman
DateTime::::2016-01-23T10:50:21Z
You are still not understanding the concept of a calculated pause. It does not start at the 1998 El Nino year except by chance. If the pause were to last long enough, the starting date of it would move backwards to the previous year, then the one before that, and so on. I believe it did actually reach back to late 1996 at one point. I agree that to measure a trend both the 1998 El Nino and the following La Nina should be omitted. You then have a much lower trend from about 2000 onwards than in the 1990s. The 1998 El Nino marked a step change upwards in GMT, followed by an almost flat trend. However, none of this addresses the question of how much temperature rise can be attributed to CO2. To my mind that is the core problem, that the IPCC have overestimated climate sensitivity to CO2 forcing. There are about 7 peer reviewed and published papers that put sensitivity at between one fifth and one seventh of the IPCC value. I'm not saying they are right, but they certainly throw considerable doubt on it. If the IPCC had got it wrong, that would be an easy excuse for why the climate models were so wrong, but the IPCC and their crew are just too reluctant to give up the idea of catastrophic global warming. About one third of all anthropogenic CO2 emissions since the start of the industrial revolution were produced during that 18 years and 8 months, and you would expect a sharp temperature rise in response, and indeed the models reflected that. However the observed temperature rise is somewhat lower even on the ground station records. Why is it so hard for the so called warmists to see that if the observed data does not support the theory, the theory needs adjusting?



