Your selective choice of data sets simply demonstrates your desire to mislead by omitting the complete picture. Your link gives the impression something dramatic is happening in sea level rise in recent years. But how about looking at sea level rise over the past 100 years, which started well before CO2 could have had any impact. Also bearing in mind that the average sea level rise since the end of the last ice age is about 1m per century. Yes, the rate has dramaticly slowed down in recent centuries. But its clear a rise of 20-30 cm or so per century is anything but dramatic. The need to be deliberately selective and misleading in your selection of data and evidence only serves to demonstrate the absence of hard evidence.



