Author::::derekcolman
DateTime::::2016-01-22T21:38:10Z
I am aware of the whole satellite data set. In it's early years it agreed approximately with the ground station sets, and NASA proclaimed it the most accurate temperature data set available. When it became obvious that it was diverging, after a period of stunned silence, NASA set about trying to disown it. This has now culminated in a group of the most alarmist scientists posting a video on YouTube vilifying it. Such is the politics of climate change. The point is that though no data set is perfect, the satellite sets by their very nature are less prone to inaccuracy than the ground station sets, which are far more adjusted and therefore more likely to be affected by human error.I have no argument with the 30 year periods, and it will be interesting to see how the satellite sets work out for the period of 2000 to 2030, but of course we have to wait another 15 years for that. It will have the advantage of not including the 1998 peak.Regarding the 18 years and 8 months pause, this is not a cherry picked period. Why is it so hard to understand that it is calculated? It is quite a simple calculation. You start with the present day, then just count backwards as far as it is possible to go without any significant warming. As such it is a variable period, which is why the warmth of 2015 has lopped a month off it.



